<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Illiteracy and Delinquency -- 12/29/95</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
December 29, 1995
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Illiteracy and Delinquency</h2></center><P> . 

[Everyone's got his own idea of the best way to reduce crime -- more  
policemen, longer sentences, more prisons, and so on. But a number of  
studies suggest that teaching criminals to read may be the best solution of  
all!] 
 <p>
The National Adult Literacy Survey, commissioned by the U.S.  
Department of Education, found in 1993 that nearly half our adult  
population are poor readers. Another U.S. Department of Education  
survey, also in 1993, disclosed that more than two-thirds of U.S.  
schoolchildren cannot read up to their grade level. Al Shanker, longtime  
president of the American Federation of Teachers, declared in 1989 that  
only 3 to 6 percent of 17- and 18-year-olds are able to read editorials and  
articles in major newspapers and write a several-page essay. He said that  
80 percent of public school graduates cannot even write a two-paragraph  
letter to a supermarket manager applying for a job. A study on illiteracy  
commissioned by the Department of Justice in l992 said that 21 million  
Americans can't read at all, 45 million are marginally illiterate, and 20  
percent of high school graduates can't read their diplomas. 
 <p>
A l 993 U.S. Department of Justice study concluded that "the major cause  
of delinquency" is reading failure, and that-children in schools are  
"denied the means to achieve the goal to read." Juvenile delinquents and  
adult prisoners who are taught to read using a traditional intensive  
phonics method show a marked decrease in behavior problems as they  
become literate. 
 <p>
With a research grant funded by the U.S. Department of Justice, Michael  
Brunner spent two years analyzing the literature on illiteracy and  
recidivism. In a new book called Retarding America: The Imprisonment  
of Potential, he comes to the chilling conclusion that reading failure is a  
major cause, rather than just a correlate, of anti-social behavior. Brunner  
found that a high percentage of incarcerated juveniles were diagnosed  
early in school as "learning disabled" even though there was no evidence  
of specific neurological abnormalities. These children never received the  
kind of reading instruction that is successful -- namely, intensive,  
systematic phonics. So they never learned how to identify sounds in  
isolation, to blend individual speech sounds into words, or to segment  
polysyllabic words into speech sounds. Brunner discovered that failure to  
learn to read is a major cause for the frustration and low self-esteem that  
lead to juvenile delinquency. 
 <p>
Brunner reports a poignant interview with an incarcerated teenage boy  
who could decipher only four words and spell two. His years in the public  
school system were a time of constant humiliation because he could not  
read. Combative behavior was the only means he could think of to keep  
his peers from laughing at him. In the correctional institution, the boy  
was taught to read with remedial intensive phonics. Another teenager,  
interviewed at Ironwood Maximum Security Prison, felt like a new  
person once he had mastered phonics and learned to read. It sounds  
incredible, but making sure children learn how to read in the first grade is  
a proven crime prevention technique! 
 <p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
