<html>
<head>
<title>Behind the Headlines</title>
<center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</h4>  
 <i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.  <br>
 F.R. Duplantier <br>
 September 21, 1995  <br>
  </i><hr>

 
<h2>The Argument Against Gun Control</h2> </center><p>
  
America cannot remain the land of the free unless it continues to be the  
home of the brave. <p> 
 
  
Fueled by anti-gun hysteria, the drive to disarm America gathered  
momentum with the assassinations of Robert Kennedy and Martin Luther  
King Jr. in 1968, the year that saw passage of the Gun Control Act. It   
neared its logical conclusion in 1981 when the Village Board of Morton  
Grove, Illinois banned the possession of all handguns and attempted to  
compel local citizens to surrender their weapons to the police. But, in the  
following year, the pendulum began to swing back the other way. In 1982  
the city council of Kennesaw. Georgia voted unanimously to require the  
head of every household to own a gun and ammunition. That year the  
incidence of burglary went down 73 percent in Kennesaw. Meanwhile, it  
was going up in Morton Grove.  <p>
  
Whether their motivation is a sincere desire to reduce the incidence of  
homicide, or a determination to render patriotic Americans defenseless,  
advocates of gun control have trouble advancing credible arguments on  
its behalf, relying instead on emotional appeals and exploiting every gun- 
related tragedy. What else can they do when FBI statistics show that most  
of the states with the highest murder rates have extensive gun control.  
while most of the states with the lowest murder rates have little or no gun  
control?  <p>
  
The pragmatic argument against gun control is simply that it doesn't  
work. Indeed, it seems to encourage crime to the extent that the  
criminally inclined are emboldened by the powerlessness of potential  
victims. But there is an even stronger moral argument, which will be  
heard more and more frequently as Americans in increasing numbers  
express their disenchantment with dependency and seek to reestablish  
their self-respect.  <p>
  
It is the argument of a brave people whose descendants very nearly  
succumbed to cowardice. As incorporated into the Declaration of  
Independence. it expresses the once self-evident truths that all people   
have the right to live, to be free, and to act in their own best interests; that  
these fights are given to us by God. not by other men; that governments  
have no other purpose than to protect these rights; and that a people can  
at any time discharge a government whose protection has burgeoned into  
oppression.  <p>
  
The possession of rights presupposes not only the responsibility for their  
proper use, but also the power to preserve them. Given the obvious  
inability of government to protect the rights of all people at all times, and   
the obvious inability of an unarmed citizenry to protect itself against a  
government that enjoys a monopoly on the use of force, it is abundantly  
clear that a free people must be armed to remain free. Americans are   
beginning to understand again that independence is a right, and bravery  
the virtue that preserves it. It's a good thing, too, because America will  
remain the land of the free only as long as it is also the home of the   
brave.  <p>
  
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free  
transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St.  
Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><br><br>
[<a href ="/townhall/columnists/welcome.html.cgi"> Columnists </a>]
</body>
