<head>
<title>Duplantier: Feminists Ignore Successful Women  -- 2/8/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

February 8, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Feminists Ignore Successful Women </h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>More than six million American women own their own businesses. Yet, for 
some strange reason, you'll never hear a feminist trumpeting these 
triumphs. </i></blockquote>
<P> 
Feminists seem determined to "wave aside the achievements of the individual 
for the collectivist utopia of group success," says Elizabeth Larson in a 
recent issue of The Freeman, a monthly journal published by the Foundation 
for Economic Education. Larson argues that such feminist-supported policies 
as affirmative action are actually detrimental to women. "The American 
working woman pays a high price for the position or promotion she receives 
from affirmative action," says Larson, and that price is "the unspoken 
assumption that she was not the 'best man' for the job." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether that assumption is warranted in a particular instance or not, the 
fact remains that affirmative action tends to make the qualifications of 
all women seem suspect -- with sad, but certain consequences. "Resentment 
against an individual case of hiring by quota ferments into resentment 
against all members of the privileged group," says Larson. Although 
affirmative action is supposed to remedy the effects of discrimination, in 
reality it only perpetuates it. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Supporters of affirmative action for women play fast and loose with their 
figures. The so-called wage gap between men and women is "neither as wide 
nor as unbridgeable as it is portrayed," notes Larson. "Once you stop 
lumping all women of all ages in all fields together and using that 
resulting dollar figure as representative of the average American working 
woman, the gap narrows. Comparing the wages of women and men of the same 
age, with similar experience, training, and years of uninterrupted time in 
their field yields a much more optimistic picture of how women fare today." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Larson says "the gaps that do still exist are likely due to the fewer 
continuous years women have been in the workforce. Women who have never 
interrupted their careers for any reason now earn at least 98 percent as 
much as their male counterparts." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Larson contends that "many feminists labor under assumptions about the 
workplace and the meaning of success that are both unreasonable and 
unrealistic. They seem to believe that making an attempt at her job in and 
of itself guarantees a woman success." It's not that easy, says Larson. 
"Just because a woman wants to be the first female CEO of her company does 
not mean she is entitled to the position, or that if she fails to make it 
that far up the corporate ladder it is someone else's fault. Luck, drive, 
brains, connections, education, and, yes, good looks, can all play a part 
in the promotions any worker -- male, or female -- receives." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
There are many women who have "genuine, free-market success stories to 
tell," but you won't hear about them from feminists, because that would 
undercut their campaign for government intervention. "An eagerness to rely 
on the government," says Elizabeth Larson, "betrays a lack of confidence in 
women's abilities to achieve financial and personal independence." 
 
     
<P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




