<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Terrorism -- 1/3/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 3, 1996
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Terrorism</h2></center><P> 

[The threat to American security posed by Libyan and Iranian terrorists 
doesn't seem to loom as large today as it did in the early 1980s, but the 
threat remains.]
<p>
Former FBI agent Ray Wannall says that Iran and Libya have held 
grudges against the United States since at least the early 1980s. "Their 
terroristic threats against the U.S. were intensified following our raid on 
Tripoli and Benghazi, Libya in 1986, the accidental shooting down of an 
Iranian Airbus in the Persian Gulf in 1988, and the U.S. downing of two 
Libyan fighter jets over the Mediterranean the following year."
<p>
Wannall recalls that early in 1985 Muammar Qaddafi urged black 
American servicemen to leave the military and form a separate army 
because the United States "must be destroyed." In a 40-minute satellite 
address from Libya to a Nation of Islam convention in Chicago, Qaddafi 
declared: "This country must be destroyed. They refuse to accept you as 
American citizens. This means you are obliged to create a separate and 
independent state." Louis Farrakhan, leader of the Nation of Islam, 
endorsed the Libyan dictator's remarks, saying, "Brother Qaddafi is a 
man the world does not understand."
<p>
In that 1985 speech, Qaddafi incited Farrakhan's followers to 
insurrection. "You have the force, you have the soldiers," said Qaddafi. 
"We are ready to give you arms, because your cause is just. We are with 
you. Don't worry. You have to trust us. We will fight together shoulder 
by shoulder. The final victory will be soon." Though claiming to have 
declined the offer of arms, Farrakhan did accept a $5 million interest-free 
loan from Qaddafi, ostensibly to underwrite a commercial enterprise to 
help black Americans create financial independence.
<p>
The Washington Times reported in 1985 that a radical Islamic 
infrastructure of terror has been established across the U.S., consisting of 
safehouses, weapons, ammunition, money, and systems to provide 
medical and legal aid, false identity papers, and transportation. Followers 
of Qaddafi and Iran's Ayatollah Khomeini man this network, ready to 
spring into action when the word comes. Appearing before Congress the 
following year, FBI Director William Webster warned that three-fourths 
of the 2,000 Libyan students in the U.S. were financed by the Libyan 
government and could constitute a terrorist threat.
<p>
Former FBI Executive Assistant Director Oliver Revell warned earlier 
this year that it is likely that a radical Islamic fundamentalist 
infrastructure has been firmly established in our country. The radical 
fundamentalists "support such organizations as Hezbollah, Hamas, and 
the Palestinian Islamic Jihad, which are directly involved in terrorism and 
violently oppose the Israeli-PLO initiative," says Revell. "These 
organizations are aided and supported by Iran, including its diplomatic 
establishments and intelligence services, which makes them even more 
dangerous."<p>

Ray Wannall says the Iranians and the Libyans "have not tempered their 
threats in recent years. Nor has Louis Farrakhan given any sign of 
rejecting Qaddafi's avowed friendship and support. Jihad, the holy war 
waged on behalf of Islam as a religious duty, is still being fought."
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
