<head>
<title>Duplantier: LOVE CANAL -- 2/22/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>


<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 22, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Love Canal</h2>


<i><blockquote>
At a recent press conference announcing that the Occidental Chemical 
Corporation had agreed to pay $129 million to clean up toxic waste at 
Love Canal, Attorney General Janet Reno observed that it was only fair 
to expect people to clean up their own mess. She neglected to mention, 
however, that government played a major role in creating this particular 
mess.

</blockquote></i>

<P>
Everyone knows that Occidental's predecessor company, Hooker 
Chemicals & Plastics, buried toxic waste at Love Canal more than 40 
years ago. What they don't know, says Michael Fumento of the 
Competitive Enterprise Institute, is that "Hooker tried desperately to 
convince the city of Niagara Falls (where Love Canal is located) not to 
build on the site." Citing a 1981 article in Reason magazine, Furnento 
recounts how the Niagara Falls school board "applied massive pressure 
to obtain the land despite Hooker's repeated warnings of potential health 
hazards. Finally, Hooker gave in and sold the land for a symbolic dollar 
bill. It insisted, though, that the land . . . was under no circumstances to 
be excavated."

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Niagara Falls ignored that stipulation. "Instead, the city decided to build 
a housing development on the site.... Then it sold the plots to 
unsuspecting home buyers." The fact is that Hooker did not endanger the 
public when it dumped its waste in an undeveloped area. "It was the 
city's choice to bring people" to that location, says Fumento. "The bad 
guy wasn't the big faceless corporation; it was your friendly city 
government."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Fumento notes that "nobody at Love Canal complained of any 
exceptional illnesses until a muckraking environmental reporter for the 
local paper began a series of articles telling the people that they were 
sitting on a toxic waste site." Then a feeding frenzy began. "The media 
descended on the town and relayed to the outside world every sneeze, 
every cough, and every ache and pain experienced by Love Canal 
residents, making it clear that they could only be caused by toxic waste." 
Bureaucrats and politicians saw an opportunity to grandstand. "The EPA 
and the governor of New York swaggered around, condemning the 
chemical company and promising to make everything better, no matter 
the cost. Ultimately, tens of millions of dollars were spent evacuating the 
residents."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Fumento reports that subsequent studies by state and federal agencies 
"found that Love Canal residents had no more illnesses than would be 
expected in any other area of similar size." Attorney General Janet Reno 
neglected to mention this at the news conference, possibly because more 
than $100 million of the Occidental settlement is going to be 
Environmental Protection Agency's Superfund, which was created in the 
wake of Love Canal hysteria. EPA Administrator Carol Browner used 
the occasion to warn that "Congress is attempting to roll back the 
environmental health protections that Superfund brought to Love Canal." 
That contention is easily refuted, says Fumento. "Since there was never 
any health threat at the Love Canal, obviously Superfund brought no 
protection there."

<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




