<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: Conservation Economics -- 4/5/96</title>
</title>

</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier

</a><br>


April 5, 1996
</i><br>

<h2>
Conservation Economics
</h2>



<P><blockquote><i>  
If environmental activists really cared about preserving endangered 
species, they wouldn't let an ideological commitment to socialism stand 
in the way.
</blockquote></i>

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
"Since 1970, conservationists have painted a dismal picture of an 
increasing struggle for survival of wildlife, with one species after another 
being pushed to the brink of extinction," says Robert J. Smith of the 
Competitive Enterprise Institute. "Why are some species disappearing 
and others thriving?" Smith argues that "the problem of overexploitation 
or overharvesting is a result of the resources being under public rather 
than private ownership." In the January issue of his organization's 
monthly newsletter, "UpDate," Smith distinguishes between "two totally 
different forms of property rights and ownership: public, communal, or 
open-access common property vs. private property. Wherever we have 
public ownership we find overuse, waste, and extinction; but private 
ownership results in sustained-yield use and preservation."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Wildlife problems resulting from public ownership have been "especially 
prevalent in America," says Smith, but less so in other parts of the world. 
"In Europe, native wildlife often belongs to private landowners or is 
managed under a combination of private and public property. Some 
European countries have fewer problems of overexploitation of wildlife, 
regardless of population pressures and economic and political systems." 
There's a lesson to be learned here, says Smith.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
An example of "how private ownership can successfully preserve wildlife 
is found on game ranches, hunting preserves, safari parks, and animal and 
bird farms." Smith contends that "these game ranches produce many 
positive results. Many of the animals they stock are rapidly disappearing 
in their native countries because of pressures resulting from a rapidly 
expanding human population. Indeed, some of the more spectacular and 
most sought-after big-game mammals may now have healthier and more 
stable populations on game ranches than in their native countries."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The reluctance of conservationists to embrace private ownership of 
wildlife is one of the biggest threats to the preservation of endangered 
species. "If the profits gained by giving hunters access to exotic game can 
provide the economic incentive for landowners to manage the animals on 
a sustained-yield basis, some species will be saved," says Smith. He notes 
that "the protection provided at some of the parks, preserves, and gardens 
has actually produced a glut of some animals. There have been well-
publicized efforts by some preserves to return their surplus animals to 
Africa." Smith predicts that "in the future the developing countries will 
be restocked with their native fauna from specimens now thriving on 
game ranches and preserves."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Conservationists need to overcome their slavish devotion to big 
government. "The problems of environmental degradation, 
overexploitation of natural resources, and depletion of wildlife all derive 
from their existence as common property resources," says Robert J. 
Smith. "Wherever we have exclusive private ownership, whether it is 
organized around a profit-seeking or nonprofit undertaking, there are 
incentives for the private owners to preserve the resource. Self-interest 
drives private property owners to careful management of their resource."



<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit  
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise  
system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of  
this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: America's  
Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105. 
</i></blockquote></blockquote>

