<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  TRUTH IN LEARNING</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
December 15, 1995
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Truth in Learning</h2></center><P>                

[The failure of our educational system -- especially our colleges and 
universities -- can be traced, ultimately, to one human flaw, arrogance.]
<P>
The tremendous popularity of the television quiz show called Wheel of 
Fortune no doubt derives from the program's ingenious design, which 
encourages contestants to delay solution of the puzzle while racking up 
points for guessing the letters that compose it. Home viewers are thereby 
assured of knowing the answer long before it is officially acknowledged. 
What keeps Wheel of Fortune fans coming back is the pleasant feeling of 
superiority home viewers enjoy each time the answer is revealed, and 
they find out it's just what they thought it was.
<P>
A similar predictability may have accounted for the tremendous 
popularity of one of the best-selling books of the 1980s, Allan Bloom's 
The Closing of the American Mind. That's the book that started an 
impressive genre of writing critical of colleges and universities. After all, 
Allan Bloom didn't really tell us anything we didn't already know. We'd 
known for years that the colleges are filled with leftist and relativistic 
ideologues. We didn't need to spend $20 on a 400-page book to find that 
out, but many of us did, and were gratified that a university professor 
had finally said what we'd been saying all along.
<P>
A lesser-known scholar named James Schall also set out to expose the 
intellectual blight in our nation's universities. His book, entitled 
Another Sort of Learning, appeared almost simultaneously with the 
paperback  release of The Closing of the American Mind, but it did not 
enjoy similar success. Here's why: Rather than make us feel superior, 
even a bit smug, by confirming our bleak assessments of contemporary 
education, Schall's book made us feel uneasy. Schall insisted, for 
instance, that "most of the important things we do not in fact learn are 
not learned because we choose not to learn them." In other words, we 
expect too much from the universities, and we've only got ourselves to 
blame for our manifest deficiencies.
<P>
Schall went even further. He suggested that a university is "not really 
equipped" to provide the education we need. He said that the university 
is "designed, consciously or unconsciously, to prevent us from 
confronting in our own lives the ultimate questions of existence and 
essence." Needless to say, Schall's radical ideas didn't go over big in 
college towns. After all, it's one thing to say that the system isn't 
working: it's another thing entirely to say it isn't meant to work. But 
that's what Schall said, emphasizing that "we meet the more ultimate 
things in our churches, in our families, in our living, in our friendships."
<P>
Schall wasn't satisfied with condemning relativism. He had to talk about 
Truth. Allan Bloom had discussed Truth too, but somehow, in Schall's 
book, Truth seemed to mean something specific. Unlike Bloom, Schall 
dared to identify the source of Truth, and to declare that revelation 
makes it available to everyone, the humbler the better. James Schall's 
book, Another Sort of Learning, addresses the first causes of the 
decline of college campuses today.
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
