<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: Property Rights Are Under Attack! -- 2/11/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

February 11, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Property Rights Are Under Attack!</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>Do Americans really own anything anymore, or is everything we possess just 
on loan to us from the federal government? </i></blockquote>
<P> 
"Mass confiscation [of personal property] has become politically 
fashionable," reports James Bovard in a recent issue of The Freeman, the 
monthly journal of the Foundation for Economic Education. "Politicians and 
the courts have created an overwhelming presumption in favor of the 
government's right to seize control over private land, private homes, 
boats, and cars, and even the cash in people's wallets." Bovard warns that 
government's power to seize private property "directly subjugates citizens 
to the capricious will" of public officials. And those officials don't need 
much of a pretext to justify their actions. Bovard says, "Thousands of 
American citizens are being stripped of their property on the basis of 
rumors and unsubstantiated assertions made by the government's confidential 
informants." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Is this the American way? Whatever happened to personal property rights and 
the presumption of innocence? How did we get to this state of affairs? 
"Beginning in 1970, Congress enacted legislation to permit government to 
seize property of Mafia organizations and big-time drug smugglers," 
explains Bovard. More forfeiture laws were enacted as the years went on, 
with the result that "federal agents can now seize private property under 
more than 200 different statutes. From 1985 to 1991, the number of federal 
seizures of property under asset forfeiture laws increased by 1500 
percent." Federal officials lost interest in crime lords and drug kingpins. 
"Unfortunately, the more forfeiture laws legislatures enacted, the less 
attention police seem to pay to major criminals," says Bovard. Today, the 
vast majority of citizens forfeiting their property to the federal 
government under drug laws "are never formally charged with any crime." 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
Bovard asserts that nowadays "the mere suspicion of a government official 
is sufficient proof to nullify all claims that a citizen legitimately owns 
his property." He notes that "forfeiture laws are turning some federal 
agents into the modern-day equivalent of horse thieves. Ranchers are being 
victimized by seizures based on allegations of violations of environmental 
laws." By confiscating the vehicles that ranchers use to earn their 
livelihood, federal agents effectively put them out of business. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
According to the Justice Department's 1992 annual report on asset seizures, 
"No property may be seized unless the government has probable cause to 
believe that it is subject to forfeiture." That sounds good in theory, says 
Bovard, but that's not the way it works. "In reality, government officials 
are seizing people's property based solely on 'hearsay' -- rumor and gossip 
-- from anonymous informants." Bovard considers it more than likely that 
some policemen have "invented anonymous informants to give them a pretext 
to take private property they covet." The old double standard comes into 
play here with a vengeance. "While government agents can use hearsay 
evidence to justify a seizure," says Bovard, "property owners are usually 
prohibited from offering hearsay evidence to support their claims." 
 
 
<P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




