<head>
<title>Duplantier LAW OF THE SEA TREATY -- 5/15/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.</i><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

<I>
May 15, 1996   
</I>

<h2> LAW OF THE SEA TREATY</h2>   
<P>
<blockquote><I>
   
The Clinton administration is trying to persuade the United States    
Senate to ratify a United Nations Treaty that Ronald Reagan refused to    
sign, with good reason, fourteen years ago!</I>   
</blockquote>

   
Despite abundant resources, America nevertheless lacks certain essential    
minerals, such as cobalt, bauxite, chromium, manganese, and platinum.    
Cobalt is essential for jet engines, magnetic materials for electronics,    
metal cutting, and mineral tools. Bauxite is essential to aluminum, and is    
also important to refractories, chemicals, packaging, mechanical    
equipment, and abrasives. Chromium is essential to metallurgical,    
refractory, and chemical industries. Manganese is essential to steel, pig    
iron, dry cell batteries, and various chemical processes. Platinum-group    
metals are essential to automobiles, chemical processing, the electrical    
industry, and petroleum refining.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;   
   
We import most of our manganese from Russia and South Africa. Yet,    
the ocean floor extending from our West Coast to Hawaii is rich in    
deposits of this mineral. U.S. security interests may depend on our access    
to such vital resources at the bottom of the sea, but the financial    
investment required to bring them to the surface is tremendous, because    
the minerals are scattered on the ocean floor at depths of as much as    
20,000 feet. Nevertheless, American mining concerns have the capital    
and the technology to take on this challenge, if they can be assured of    
realizing a profit in the venture.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;   
   
The Law of the Sea Treaty, currently being pushed by the Clinton    
administration, would give Third World nations control over the    
development and use of the deep seabed mineral resources now being    
mined by American firms. The Treaty's international controls and    
regulations would hamper the efforts of U.S. ocean-mining companies to    
continue harvesting strategic ocean minerals essential to our industry    
and to our military defense.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;   
   
The Law of the Sea Treaty would surrender major political and strategic    
advantages to Russia, which is self-sufficient in the minerals that    
America extracts from the ocean floor. The Treaty would deny U.S.    
ownership of ocean minerals, while forcing American companies to use    
their technology and capital to mine these minerals for the benefit of    
unfriendly, anti-American countries.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;   
   
The Law of the Sea Treaty would establish an International Seabed    
Authority, which would set both general production controls and specific    
production limits for ocean mining sites. Any American corporation    
intent on making the tremendous investment involved in mining the    
ocean floor would first have to seek approval from the Executive Council    
of the International Seabed Authority. If its request is approved, the    
American corporation would begin operations with the understanding    
that one-half of the approved mining tract will be set aside so that an    
international mining operation (set up by the Seabed Authority) can use    
the American company's geological data, technology, and money to    
compete against it!
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;   
   
The United Nations Law of the Sea Treaty threatens the sovereignty and    
security of our nation. It also jeopardizes the legitimate financial    
interests of U.S. businesses and the health of our country's economy. Any    
American politician who supports this treaty has some explaining to do.   
<P>   
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit    
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-   
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free    
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:    
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</I>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>


<P><br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
