<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier "CAREERS" Bill -- 5/24/96	 </title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.</i><br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

<I>
May 24, 1996
</I>

<h2>"CAREERS" BILL</h2>
<P>
<blockquote><I>  
  
Americans are lucky to live in a society in which education is available   
to all and the individual is free to choose what he will make of himself.   
In totalitarian countries, the State determines who will get the benefit of   
education and what job opportunities a person will have.</BLOCKQUOTE></I>
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
There is no clamor in the heartland for radical restrictions on the   
freedom Americans enjoy to improve their minds and plot the course of   
their careers. There is no grassroots support for turning our public   
schools into vocational training centers for a docile national workforce.   
How, then, to explain the progress of the CAREERS bill and the   
Workforce Development Act?
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
Under these bipartisan education bills now moving through Congress,   
the Federal Government would collect taxes, issue educational   
regulations, and then pass the proceeds and the power to State   
Governors, circumventing their legislatures altogether. This massive   
legislation would restructure public schools throughout America,   
building on the Goals 2000 and School-to-Work Acts passed in 1994.   
H.R.1617 (known as the CAREERS bill) passed the House last   
September by a vote of 345 to 79, and its companion S. 143 (called the   
Workforce Development Act) passed the Senate in October by 95 to 2. 
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
  
More than 60 Republican members of the Missouri House of   
Representatives recently fired off a letter to House Speaker Newt   
Gingrich, objecting to the fact that H.R. 1617 "centralizes unprecedented   
powers at the federal level" and "supersedes state laws and further takes   
us, the local elected officials of the people of this state, out of the process   
of education." Noting that the CAREERS act "amends out the state   
legislature, replacing it with the Governor," the State Representatives   
assert that "this practice of avoiding the Legislature is unacceptable and   
flies in the face of the principle of local control of education." 
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
  
The Missouri Republicans also charge that unelected bureaucrats are   
attempting to grab power over school curricula though a grant   
application process. The grant applications that Governors now submit   
in a bid for federal funds bind the states to conform to "standards" and   
"assessments" written by federal or state bureaucrats insulated from the   
influence of local citizens and their elected representatives. The grant   
applications also bind the states to spend money not yet appropriated by   
their legislatures.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
Fourteen California State Senators also dispatched a letter calling on   
Congress to "kill" H.R. 1617. They too objected to the transfer of   
legislative prerogative into the hands of the Governor, and opposed the   
establishment of a "National Electronic Data Base" to monitor the   
progress of students along predetermined career paths.
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois voted for the CAREERS bill last year, but   
has since reversed himself. He is now urging the repeal of Goals 2000   
and the School to Work Act, as well as the defeat of H.R. 1617 and   
S.143. Such legislation, he contends, would turn schoolchildren into   
"guinea pigs who will become the human resources for the global labor   
market." Is that really what we want for our children?
<BR>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;  
  
<P>  
 <i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit   
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-  
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free   
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to:   
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</I>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>


