<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Abolish Education Department -- 1/10/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 10, 1996
<br></i><hr><h2>Abolish the Department of Education</h2></center><P> 
[Abolishing the Department of Education would curb the federal 
government's baleful influence on public schools and save as much as 
$70 billion a year in taxpayers' money.] 
 
 <P>
Early in the 1976 presidential elections, the National Education 
Association threw its important support behind a relatively unknown 
candidate named Jimmy Carter. The NEA endorsement gave visibility to 
the obscure, one-term Georgia governor, adding momentum to his 
ultimately-successful campaign. The endorsement came with a price, 
however, one that President Carter gladly paid. The establishment of the 
federal Department of Education was the quid pro quo that the National 
Education Association received for the push it provided to the political 
presumptions of a pandering peanut farmer. 
 <P>
Of course, the federal government was meddling in education long before 
then, but the creation of a separate cabinet-level department has greatly 
exacerbated the problem. Congress now appropriates $70 billion per year 
for what it calls education. Roughly half of this amount goes to the 
administration of 244 separate programs in the Department of Education. 
The rest is spent by 30 other federal agencies on 308 overlapping 
programs. There are more than 90 separate federal preschool and child 
care programs, administered by eleven different agencies and 20 different 
offices. There are 86 separate federal teacher training programs, 
administered by nine different departments. There are at least 46 separate 
federal youth development programs, administered by eight different 
agencies. None of these programs is necessary, and most of them are 
redundant. 
 <P>
The Federal Government's 30-year experiment with education funding 
has failed miserably. Illiteracy has reached epidemic proportions, and 
Scholastic Aptitude Test scores have dropped so dramatically that the 
Educational Testing Service is now adding nearly 100 points to every 
score to conceal this embarrassing decline. Abolishing the Department of 
Education will not adversely affect our public schools, which flourished 
before the department was created and will survive its termination. 
Federal spending in public schools is only about six percent of their total 
budget, and precious little of it supports legitimate academic pursuits. 
Layoffs of superfluous administrative personnel could easily offset a six-
percent downsizing. 
 <P>
Establishing a federal Department of Education may have worked 
wonders for the National Education Association, but it has done nothing 
positive for America's public schools. In fact, it has had an entirely 
deleterious effect, further weakening local control and adding costly 
government regulations at the expense of academic curricula. The fact 
that it hasn't worked is a good judgment for abolishing the Department of 
Education, but the best argument of all is that the Department is simply 
unconstitutional. The U.S. Constitution  makes no mention of education, 
and provides no authority for the federal government to meddle in local 
schools. The federal government has inserted itself into numerous areas 
beyond its constitutional jurisdiction, and it's time for Americans to insist 
that it return to its proper concerns. Eliminating the Department of 
Education would be a good start. 
 <p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
<br><br>
