<html><head>
<title>Duplantier: UNCHANGING TRUTHS -- 4/18/96</title></head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES  </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.   <br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
April 18, 1996
</i><br>
<h2>
UNCHANGING TRUTHS
</h2>

<P><blockquote><i>  
The best protection against the designs of demagogues, do-gooders, and 
other self-styled reformers is a  firm grasp of eternal verities.
</blockquote></i>
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The Greek philosopher Aristotle argued that the sovereignty of the law 
must supersede the sovereignty of the ruler. The law is a higher authority 
than the ruler because it; proceeds from a higher authority. "He who 
commands that law should rule [commands] that God and reason alone 
should rule," said Aristotle. Democracies inevitably decline when they 
cease to respect this higher authority and place the interests of any one 
group above the common good.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The English philosopher John Locke went to great lengths to distinguish 
liberty from license and to demonstrate that the law is the liberator, not 
the oppressor, of man: "Law, in its true notion, is not so much the 
limitation as the direction of a free and intelligent agent to his proper 
interest, and prescribes no farther than is for the general good of those 
under that law." Locke argued that "the end of the law is not to abolish or 
restrain but to preserve and enlarge freedom," though he emphasized that 
freedom is not "a liberty for every man to do what he [pleases]."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In order to live, legally, at someone else's expense, it is necessary to turn 
the law into "an instrument of plunder," observed the French economist 
Frederic Bastiat. No matter how noble the justification, once the premise 
is accepted that a government can expropriate the wealth of some of its 
citizens and dispense it to others, theft has been legalized, and the signal 
has been sent that nothing is secure. Bastiat considered this the greatest 
evil to which any society can be subjected, but recognized it as the 
ultimate goal of all greedy men and do-gooders.
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
French social psychologist Gustave Le Bon argued that all forms of 
government enshrine one or the other of "two different and opposing 
fundamental principles -- individualism and collectivism. By 
individualism, man is left to himself; his initiative is carried to a 
maximum and that of the state to a minimum. By collectivism a man's 
least actions are directed by the state . . . the individual possesses no 
initiative; all the acts of his life are mapped out." Le Bon had no 
difficulty determining which of these two conflicting principles leads to 
greater results: "The peoples among whom individualism is most highly 
developed are by this fact alone at the head of civilization."
<BR>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
American patriot John T. Flynn urged his countrymen to "stop 
apologizing for our capitalist society." We should take no more steps 
down the road to socialism, he said, and turn out of office any politician 
who tries to lead us in that direction. Flynn pointed out "that we are in a 
social war, and that we must fight it as such." He said we should "put an 
end to the orgy of spending that is rapidly bankrupting the nation," quit 
letting bureaucrats plan our economy, and instead let "our free system of 
private enterprise operate at its fullest capacity."
<P><P>

<i>
Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit 
educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free-
enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free 
transcript of this broadcast, send a self-addressed, stamped envelope to: 
America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.
</i>

</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
</body>
