<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Affirmative Action  -- 5/8/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 8, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Affirmative Action</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
More and more minority members are voicing their opposition to 
affirmative action, rejecting the patronizing racial preferences that 
are supposed to benefit them in college admissions and business 
employment.
</i></blockquote>
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
In February, an initiative prohibiting preferential treatment on the 
state and local level qualified for the November ballot in California. 
In March, a federal appeals court rejected the use of racial 
preferences in determining admissions to the University of Texas law 
school. Even as we speak, legislation is pending in Congress that 
would prohibit the use of racial preferences in the hiring of federal 
employees and the awarding of federal contracts. What's going on in 
the state legislatures, the federal courts, and the Congress?
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
What's happening is that minority members themselves are becoming 
increasingly vocal in their opposition to racial preferences, 
recognizing these condescending concessions as the ultimate form of 
racial prejudice -- and rejecting the pandering posture of the self-
appointed minority leaders who promote them. With this groundswell of 
opposition among the supposed beneficiaries of racial preferences, it 
has now become politically feasible to denounce the injustice of 
affirmative action.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Terry Eastland is the author of a new book called<i> Ending Affirmative 
Action: The Case for Colorblind Justice.</i> In a recent editorial in the 
Wall Street Journal, Eastland observes that racial preferences "have 
never enjoyed majority support and are now in serious political 
trouble." For one thing, there's simply no denying that racial 
preferences are discriminatory. "Whatever might be said in support of 
preferences, they necessarily discriminate against those who lack the 
'right' race or sex. There is no getting around this fact," says 
Eastland, noting that the white female plaintiff denied admission to 
the University of Texas law school "had academic credentials superior 
to most of the black and Mexican-American students admitted under an 
affirmative action plan."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
While encouraging what is called "reverse discrimination," preferences 
rarely provide any substantial remedy for actual discrimination 
against minorities. "Because preferences are often a response to 
presumed discrimination on the part of a company, a government, or 
society generally, they move the focus away from the real instances of 
discrimination," says Eastland. Not only that, but they tend to 
benefit the most gifted minority members, leaving the truly 
disadvantaged in some ways worse off than before.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Affirmative action has halted, and in fact reversed, progress toward 
the color-blind society that civil rights activists once claimed as 
their goal. "Preferences have made it harder to overcome the tendency 
. . . of judging people in terms of their racial and ethnic groups," 
says Eastland. The irrationality and injustice of affirmative action 
is apparent to any thinking person, and that is why "substantial 
numbers (sometimes large majorities) of those typically eligible for 
preferential treatment -- African-Americans, Hispanics, and Asian 
Americans -- tell pollsters they are opposed to preferences." Eastland 
concludes that "only law that neither advantages nor disadvantages on 
account of race or ethnicity is law that can equally protect everyone 
in our increasingly diverse nation."
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




