</DOCHDR>
<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Medical Savings Accounts -- 1/4/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 4, 1996
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Medical Savings Accounts</h2></center><P> 

[Medical Savings Accounts are an idea whose time has come. By 
returning control over medical choices to the individual, MSAs should 
rein in the spiraling costs of health care.]
<p>
Peter Ferrara of the National Center for Policy Analysis says that "health 
care costs are out of control" because the wrong people are paying the 
bills. The patients, the ones receiving medical care, do not generally pay 
their own bills. The bills are paid, for the most part, by third parties -- 
employers, insurance companies, or the government. The average 
American pays only one-fifth of his own health care costs. "Someone else 
pays the rest," says Ferrara, and that third-party payment system is what 
is driving up health care costs. Americans simply have no personal 
incentive for monitoring the costs of their health care and shopping 
around for less expensive alternatives.
<p>
The solution is simple: Take control over health care away from third 
parties and give it back to the people who are using it. Give them a 
personal, financial incentive for keeping costs down. Ferrara says it is 
only human nature for people to be careless, even extravagant shoppers 
"if we are spending someone else's money." And it's only natural for 
doctors and other health care providers to encourage us to take advantage 
of extra tests and procedures -- just to be on the safe side -- "if they know 
that we are not paying the bills." But Americans spend their own money 
in every other marketplace, and they make wiser decisions when they do 
so. Why, then, is the marketplace of medical care different from all the 
others?
<p>
1996 looks to be the year that Congress begins restoring economic sanity 
to our health care system. The Archer-Jacobs bill will encourage 
individuals and their employers to make tax-free deposits into Medical 
Savings Accounts (MSAs), which employees can draw on to cover 
ordinary health expenses. MSAs will let Americans choose the care they 
want and spend their health care dollars as they see fit, thereby providing 
a huge incentive to keep health costs down.
<p>
With Medical Savings Accounts, employees would be spending their own 
money for non-catastrophic health care. As a result, Peter Ferrara says, 
"they would have excellent financial incentives to control the cost of such 
care. They would seek to avoid unnecessary care, look for quality plus 
value in doctors and hospitals, and consider whether the services were 
worth the prices." Medical Savings Accounts would have other benefits 
too, such as reduced administrative costs.
<p>
If Americans switch to Medical Savings Accounts in large numbers, 
health care spending will decline dramatically. MSAs will give 
consumers more choices and more control in health care decisions. These 
accounts will be portable too, not linked to continued employment at a 
specific location. MSA funds can be applied to any type of health care, 
and are not subject to the approval of insurers or health maintenance 
organizations. Medical Savings Accounts will harness the power of our 
remarkable free-enterprise system to make American medical care 
affordable again.<p>
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
