<head>
<title>Duplantier: Implications Of The VMI Court Case -- 2/15/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
February 15, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Implications Of The VMI Court Case </h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>A Supreme Court decision favoring Attorney General Janet Reno's Justice 
Department in the VMI sex-discrimination case could open up a can of worms. </i></blockquote>
<P> 
For the past 20 years, the Supreme Court has treated sex-discrimination 
cases differently from race-discrimination cases. In race cases, the Court 
applies "strict scrutiny," under the assumption that racial classifications 
are inherently "suspect" and unconstitutional (except, of course, when 
affirmative action is involved). Up till now, the Court has not considered 
gender discrimination to be inherently suspect and has applied what it 
calls "intermediate scrutiny" to cases of this nature. This standard seems 
to have worked well, and there is no evidence that this approach is either 
unworkable or unjust. 

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
As part of its effort to force the Virginia Military Institute (VMI) to 
open its doors to women, the Justice Department under Attorney General 
Janet Reno has asked the Supreme Court to add sex to its list of "suspect 
classes," thereby requiring the Court to apply "strict scrutiny" when 
considering cases involving charges of sex discrimination. Applying strict 
scrutiny to the VMI case would lead not only to the sexual integration of 
VMI, but to the sexual integration of all single-sex colleges. The fact 
that most single-sex colleges are women's colleges poses a dilemma for 
feminists and other politically-correct types. Many have no problem 
advocating the forced integration of men's colleges, but recognize that 
applying such a policy even-handedly would mean the elimination of 
women-only colleges as well. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
A Court ruling that strict scrutiny must be applied in gender cases would 
invite lawsuits against every public and private institution in America 
that makes distinctions between men and women. The effect on U.S. Armed 
Forces would be revolutionary. Our military services now provide separate 
facilities for men and women. This would be a no-no under strict scrutiny. 
The strength and endurance standards for men and women in the military are 
now substantially different. How could this be justified under strict 
scrutiny? Leave and discharge policies are different for men and women, 
recognizing pregnancy as a circumstance to be given special consideration. 
Military regulations regarding clothing and personal appearance are 
different for the two sexes. Such distinctions would not be tolerated in an 
irrational world of coercive uniformity. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
What about women's athletic programs at co-ed schools and colleges? Would 
they have to be merged with the men's programs? Would an equal number of 
boys and girls be required for every team? Would they have to share locker 
rooms and showers? Every such consideration raises the specter of a 
thousand lawsuits. 
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; 
If the Supreme Court decides to apply strict scrutiny in sex-discrimination 
cases, what will the impact be on homosexual issues such as military 
service, same-sex marriage, and adoption? Will prohibitions against 
government funding of abortion be considered sexist? We would not have to 
ask such questions if the Supreme Court could be trusted to resist the 
temptation of judicial activism. 
 
<P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>

