<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier:  Privatizing Prisons  -- 5/9/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 9, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>Privatizing Prisons</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
Privately run correctional facilities are cheaper, and better 
managed, than public prisons. There's only one reason there aren't 
more of them in America: politics.
</i></blockquote>

<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Privately owned or operated prisons "are widespread throughout the 
United States," observes Steven Loux, a policy analyst for the 
Pennsylvania House of Representatives. In a report published by the 
Key State's Commonwealth Foundation, Loux presents evidence showing 
that "such private facilities are advantageous to governments because 
they save a great deal of money, perhaps more than 10 percent per year 
in operating costs as compared to equivalent public facilities." Not 
only that, but "private prisons meet, if not surpass, the quality of 
services for prisoners and the protection to the general public 
provided by public prisons."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Loux argues that "government is simply not capable of delivering, 
running, and regulating services either as efficiently or as 
effectively as are private firms." For one thing, government does not 
have the benefit of the price system to help guide its decisions. 
Conversely, the private sector is not subject to the political 
considerations that often militate against cost-effective decisions in 
state bureaucracies. "Since political actors do not suffer economic 
pain from operating inefficient businesses, unlike private actors, the 
temptation to substitute the goals of politically influential players 
for cost-effectiveness is overwhelming," says Loux. "The authorities, 
the executive and the legislature, use their monopoly power over the 
delivery of prison services to assist certain ends -- those of 
politicians, bureaucrats, and prison employees."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Even though government itself does not respond automatically to profit 
considerations, it can take advantage of the profit-orientation of 
private-sector suppliers. "Profit can be used to discipline private 
firms in ways that it cannot discipline public bureaucracies," says 
Loux. "In fact, market competition can push private firms to not only 
meet government guidelines, but even exceed them." Such are the 
wonders of renewable contracts. "State bureaucracies cannot be fired," 
Loux laments, "but private firms that contract with the state can."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The reason that private prisons are more economical to operate than 
public facilities is not because they pay their employees less. In 
fact, the evidence indicates that "private prison firms generally do 
offer equivalent salaries and benefits for individual employees." Loux 
cites "significantly different benefit programs" and "lower absentee 
rates among private employees" as two of the cost advantages of 
private prisons. "Economies of scale," he adds, "can play a role in 
reducing the cost of private prisons. Private firms can purchase in 
bulk for their entire operation, and can do so with less bureaucratic 
involvement in comparison to public agencies."
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
There are other reasons, as well. Loux notes that "government 
agencies, in their desire to maintain their level of functioning in 
the upcoming year, want to prevent any decrease in their funding. 
Consequently, any surplus funding at the end of the year must be spent 
in some way." Also, "private firms, because they can be terminated and 
because they face competition, have the incentive to cater their 
operations to government cost standards."
 <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
<a href="/townhall/tbut.map">
<img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0">
</a></center>
<P>
