<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Spiritual Renewal -- 1/1/96</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>
January 1, 1996
<br></i><hr>
<h2>Spiritual Renewal</h2></center><P> 

[Today's the first day of the new year -- the perfect time to examine our 
personal weaknesses and the shortcomings of our society, and resolve to 
fix what needs fixing.]
<p>
In an essay published in the November issue of Hillsdale College's 
monthly journal, Imprimis, former Education Secretary William Bennett 
says that the last 30 years have been a period of cultural decline for 
America. During the last three decades, he says, "there was a 560 percent 
increase in violent crime; more than a 400 percent increase in illegitimate 
births; a quadrupling in divorces; a tripling of the percentage of children 
living in single-parent homes: more than a 200 percent increase in the 
teenage suicide rate; and a drop of 75 points in the average SAT scores of 
high school students." When it comes to social pathology, America sets 
the global pace. "We are at, or near, the top in rates of abortions, 
divorces, and unwed births," says Bennett. "We lead the industrialized 
world in murder, rape, and violent crime. And in elementary and 
secondary education, we are at, or near, the bottom in achievement 
scores."<p>

There are other, harder-to-measure "signs of decay." Bennett suggests 
that "there is a coarseness, a callousness, a cynicism. a banality, and a 
vulgarity to our time" and laments in particular the deleterious effect on 
children. "We live in a culture which at times seems almost dedicated to 
the corruption of the young, to assuring the loss of their innocence before 
their time," he says. Where are the protesters? Why doesn't anyone do 
anything? "We have become inured to the cultural rot that is setting in," 
concludes Bennett. "People are experiencing atrocity overload, losing 
their capacity for shock, disgust, and outrage."
<p>
Bennett insists that "the real crisis of our time is spiritual." He says that 
"our desires are turned toward the wrong things. And only when we turn 
them toward the right things -- toward enduring, noble, spiritual things -- 
will things get better." That's going to be rather difficult as long as there 
persists "a disturbing reluctance in our time to talk seriously about 
matters spiritual and religious." Bennett says that, "when millions of 
people stop believing in God, or when their belief is so attenuated as to 
be belief in name only, enormous public consequences follow. And when 
this is accompanied by an aversion to spiritual language by the political 
and intellectual class, the public consequences are even greater."
<p>
William Bennett recommends four steps toward "spiritual renewal." The 
first is to recognize the "intrinsic limits to what the state can do, 
particularly when it comes to imparting virtue, and forming and forging 
character, and providing peace to souls." The second is to reinvest public 
policy with "our deepest beliefs." The third is to "recover a sense of the 
fundamental purpose of education," which is moral instruction. Last, says 
Bennett, "we need to return religion to its proper place" in society -- no 
matter how much it may disconcert those who flee from faith.
<p>                           <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p>
