<html>
<head>
<title>Duplantier: Welfare Reform/GA & OH -- 6/12/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>
<a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>
<b>BEHIND THE HEADLINES</b><BR>
          

<i>
Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>
June 21, 1996<br><p></i>
<h2>Welfare Reform/GA & OH</h2>
<i><blockquote>
<P>
Georgia and Ohio offer two examples of how states are  
moving toward welfare reform.
</I></Blockquote><P>

"Many of the welfare reforms implemented in Georgia in  
recent years lack the boldness of initiatives in other states and  
contain too many exceptions to be truly effective," contends  
Kelly McCutchen of the Georgia Public Policy Foundation in  
Atlanta. Nevertheless, they have had an effect, combining  
with a bustling economy to reduce the welfare rolls by 6,000  
families in a single year. 
 <p>
"Probably the greatest problem facing Georgia's welfare  
system is the state's illegitimacy rate," says McCutchen in the  
May issue of Alternatives in Philanthropy, published by the  
Capital Research Center. The state began to address this  
problem in 1994 by denying cash benefits "to unwed teen  
mothers who choose to live on their own," notes McCutchen.  
"The following year, the number of teen mothers living  
independently dropped by 50 percent." In 1996, the state  
stopped its perverse practice of increasing benefits "to  
welfare recipients who have additional children." 
 <p>
The state should not encourage illegitimacy, nor should it  
subsidize indolence. "Able-bodied welfare recipients who  
quit or refuse to take full-time jobs face a reduction in  
benefits,'' says McCutchen. Under the state's latest initiative,  
called Work First, Georgia is "advising social workers that  
finding jobs for recipients is their number-one objective. It is  
also offering businesses tax credits and subsidies, giving  
them an incentive to hire and train welfare recipients." 
 <p>
McCutchen argues that there are "three key elements of  
welfare reform." The first is establishment of paternity. "The  
state," she says, "must send a clear message to teenage boys  
that they will be held financially responsible for any children  
they engender." The second key element of welfare reform is  
benefit reduction. "Welfare recipients should not be better off  
than those who work," she says. The third element is a work  
requirement. "Welfare recipients must not be allowed to stay  
at home and collect benefits." The ultimate objective of  
welfare reform, however, is to get community-based  
organizations back in the driver's seat. "When government  
moved into social welfare," notes McCutchen, "other  
institutions -- families, businesses, churches, and charities --  
were shunted aside. They must once again assume primary  
roles." 
<p> 
In the same issue of Alternatives in Philanthropy, Samuel  
Staley and Douglas Hyne of the Buckeye Institute for Public  
Policy Solutions in Dayton report that General Assistance in  
Ohio "began to be phased out in 1992 and was eliminated in  
1995. This has already saved the state $900 million," they  
observe. Ohio has also implemented a program called JOBS,  
which stands for Job Opportunities and Basic Skills. The  
program "requires a large number of welfare recipients to  
enroll in job-training programs. Refusal to participate results  
in a loss of welfare benefits,'' say Staley and Hyne.  
"Combined with state-mandated self-sufficiency contracts  
that outline steps recipients must take to prepare for  
employment, Ohio's JOBS participation sanctions are  
considered some of the toughest in the nation." 
<P>
<center># # # # #</center>
<P>

