<head>
<title>Duplantier:  College Education  -- 5/3/96</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a>

<B>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </B><BR>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>

<a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a><br>

May 3, 1996
<br></i>

<h2>College Education</h2>
 


<P>
<blockquote><i>
The National Association of Scholars has just published a devastating 
report on the dumbing down of 50 top undergraduate colleges and 
universities in America.
</i></blockquote>
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Comparing the years 1914, 1939, 1964, and 1993, the National 
Association of Scholars concludes that students at our country's elite 
institutions of higher learning no longer receive a comprehensive 
liberal-arts education. The universities have simply purged from the 
curriculum many of the required courses that provide the historical, 
cultural, political and scientific basics of our society.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The number of mandatory courses plummeted from an average of 10 in 
1914 to fewer than three in 1993. Students are rarely required now to 
take basic survey courses in key disciplines. Few of today's courses 
require prerequisites, thereby diminishing the cumulative impact of a 
college education. In 1914, universities offered an average of only 23 
courses per institution that did not require a prerequisite course; 
today, the number is 582. Only 12 percent of universities now require 
a thesis or comprehensive examination to get a bachelor's degree. As 
late as 1964, more than half of universities did.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Few colleges teach writing or mathematics any more, a fact that is 
evidenced by the appalling number of graduates who can neither draft a 
coherent memo nor keep a basic ledger. In 1914, nearly all 
universities had required courses in English composition; today, it's 
only 36 percent. In 1914, 82 percent of the universities had 
traditional mathematics requirements; now, only 12 percent do. As late 
as 1964, more than 70 percent of the institutions required at least 
one course in the natural sciences; that figure has now fallen to only 
34 percent. In 1914, 90 percent of our elite colleges required 
history; now only one of the 50 schools has a required history course. 
Literature courses were required at 75 percent of the institutions in 
1914; today, not one of the "best" institutions has a literature 
requirement.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
Meanwhile, the total number of courses offered at undergraduate 
institutions has quintupled since 1914. That quantity, unfortunately, 
does not translate into quality. The majority of these additional 
courses feature arcane subjects of interest, and profit, only to the 
dilettantes who offer them. Many courses don't even offer college-
level material, but seek instead to remedy the many deficiencies of 
the average high school education. Sometimes these courses are called 
"remedial," but the institutions prefer euphemisms such as "second 
tier" and "sub-freshman." Unheard of prior to 1939, today such make-up 
courses are offered in 70 percent of the elite universities, and most 
of them award college credit.
<BR> 
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;
The National Association of Scholars concludes that our best colleges 
and universities now turn out graduates who are painfully ignorant of 
western civilization and heritage. They do not learn the highlights of 
our history, they do not understand the implications of our political 
and economic systems, and they cannot appreciate our literary and 
artistic legacies. Because our colleges have failed us, we now risk 
losing the common bond that unites us as Americans.
<P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i>

<P>
</blockquote></blockquote>




<P> <br><center>
