<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  SPIES ELUDE U.S. SECURITY</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>November 24, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>Spies Elude U.S. Security</h2></center><P>

[The John Walker spy case shocked America. How did Walker manage to 
steal so many of our county's secrets and pass them on to the Soviets for 
18 years without being detected?]
<p>
How did John Walker get away with his treacherous activities? The 
answer is simple: "The U.S. security system does not work." <p>That's the 
conclusion of George P. Morse, a security consultant with half a century 
of experience. Morse considers it likely that "American secrets are still 
being compromised in ways similar to those which John Walker found so 
easy and effective to employ, for there is really no effective U.S. 
government security system in place to stem the hemorrhaging." In a 
new book called America Twice Betrayed Morse concludes that our 
nation's security system is "unsound and unworkable and should be 
abolished and replaced."
<p>
A veteran of 30 years' service with the OSS and CIA, Morse contends 
that the apprehension of spies like Walker has resulted more often from 
luck than vigilance. "The great majority of spies and enemy agents have 
actually been uncovered by accident." he observes, "or through exposure 
by the subject's relatives or defectors from the intelligence services of 
other nations. They have not generally been uncovered by our official 
government security, investigative. or intelligence systems." In fact. says 
Morse. "the way security has traditional v been conceived and organized 
by the U.S. government makes it virtually impossible to protect our 
secrets."
<p>
In his book. America Twice Betrayed. Morse proposes a new system of 
U.S. government security to "remedy many of the failures of the past 
[and] at the same time substantiallv reduce both the monetary and 
human costs associated with security." What is needed, says Morse, is "a 
total rethinking of our basic approach to security." His first step would be 
to eliminate the "wasteful and counter-productive" full field investigation 
of all applicants for federal employment. Such an investigation "creates 
the illusion that the people investigated and then 'cleared' will always be 
loyal and honest." says Morse. "It provides a false sense of security 
which enables management and staff to avoid [their obligation to 
maintain] constant vigilance."
<p>
Instead, Morse would require the applicant "to offer proof of both 
suitability and trustworthiness and loyalty." Standard reference checks 
would be followed by an intensive interview. drug-screening. and a 
polygraph examination. "Polygraph tests -- and the fear of having to 
undergo one -- are arnong the few really effective tools available to the 
government to deter and detect treason or prevarication." Says Morse, who argues that "applicants seeking government employment and security 
clearance must, as a condition of their employment, accept reasonable 
limits of privacy and their constitutional rights against self-
incrimination."
<p>
Morse also calls for the development of "an appropriate and 
comprehensive set of standards that state concretely what is and what is 
not acceptable to qualify for a U.S. government security clearance." The 
most pressing need. however, is for a dramatic improvement in "the 
abysmal quality of management exercised by the Executive Branch from 
the President on down."
<p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
