<html><head>
<title>U.S. Gets Pitiful Returns on U.N. Investment -- Duplantier</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4>
<i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br>
F.R. Duplantier <br>
October 19, 1995 <br></i>
<hr>
<h2>U.S. Gets Pitiful Returns on U.N. Investment</h2></center>
<P>
 
 
The United States spent more than three and a half billion dollars on the  
United Nations in 1994, which included a billion dollars just to support  
the UN's so-called "peacekeeping" operations and nearly two billion  
dollars' worth of military support services. What did we get for all those  
billions? Not much! 
        <P>
"The UN has been, and will continue to be, of only marginal relevance to  
international peace and security," says Thomas Sheehy of the Heritage  
Foundation. "Suggesting otherwise only sets the stage for future policy  
debacles involving the U.S. military." Sheehy argues that "UN  
peacekeeping turns disastrous when it takes the form of 'peacemaking."'  
That's because "UN forces quickly become just another group of  
combatants," fighting at a tremendous disadvantage under UN rules of  
engagement. 
                         <P>
Sheehy points out that "the countries providing peacekeepers have  
considerably less interest in the conflicts than do the forces their troops  
are fighting. As casualties are incurred, pressure mounts to bring the  
troops home," he observes. "The result is often a half-hearted and  
ultimately futile operation that suffers casualties in vain, as the U.S. did  
in Somalia." Sheehy adamantly rejects suggestions that "U.S. hesitancy to  
intervene in Bosnia and elsewhere . . . is immoral. The 'immoral' policy,"  
he insists, "is to suffer casualties in a conflict with no bearing to  
American national security and soon after to abandon the U.S.  
commitment, as was done in Somalia." 
                                  <P>
The Clinton administration argues that the U.S. would be forced "to act  
alone or not at all" if it refused to participate in UN operations. This is  
simply not true. "The U.S. has acted in concert with allies in most of its  
international conflicts," Sheehy observes. The main concern of UN  
boosters like the President is obviously "not for American security, but  
for the prestige of the UN, which suffers considerably without active  
American participation." According to Sheehy, "Collective action on a  
regional basis, such as in NATO and during the Persian Gulf War,  
whether or not it is sanctioned by the UN, undoubtedly is the best way to  
maintain international peace and stability." 
                                               <P>
Charles Lichenstein, also of the Heritage Foundation, warns that the UN  
"is reinventing what used to be called 'peacekeeping.' In the last several  
years, that do-good concept has been stretched to encompass a range of  
UN operations that typically involve the use of force, even the waging of  
war." The term "peacekeeping" now means "almost anything . . . that the  
UN wants it to mean." Lichenstein says as many as 70,000 U.S. military  
personnel currently participate in this misnamed process. "Some are  
serving in war zones, some are offshore or in aerial surveillance and  
interdiction missions, some are in support roles. But all are serving under  
the authority only of UN Security Council resolutions as implemented by  
the U.S. commander-in-chief." Lichenstein concludes that it would be  
better for the U.S. to "act alone" than to get caught up in "ill-defined,  
open-ended 'peace' operations that arguably exceed the UN's authority  
and certainly exceed its capabilities or demonstrated competence." 
 <p>                                                  <P>
<i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br>
