<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  NAFTA BAD FOR AMERICAN WORKERS</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center><h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>December 1, 1995<br></i><hr><h2>NAFTA Bad for American Workers</h2></center><P>

[It is estimated that nearly one million Americans lost their jobs this year 
as a direct result of the North American Free Trade Agreement (known as 
NAFTA). How many more American workers will have to suffer the 
same fate before our leaders admit they made a mistake?] 
 <p>
NAFTA has taken a terrible toll on the American economy, and the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (known as GATT) will only 
make matters worse, says William Gill of the American Coalition for 
Competitive Trade. Gill points out that "the United States is currently 
running record trade deficits with Mexico, after years of chalking up 
trade surpluses against that country." Of even greater concern is "the 
continued migration of our industrial plants to Mexico, which every day 
robs us of more jobs." An estimated one million jobs will have been lost 
by the end of this year. In spite of their rosy, pre-NAFTA predictions, 
giant American companies like Mattel, Allied Signal, General Electric. 
Procter & Gamble, Scott Paper, and Zenith have failed to create the 
thousands of new jobs in the United States that they promised. Instead, 
they have laid off American workers. 
 <p>
NAFTA hasn't done Mexico and Canada any good either, says Gill. "In 
Mexico, hundreds of thousands of poor farmers are being driven off the 
land and the middle class is collapsing under interest rates which in some 
cases are well over 100 percent. Conditions have become so bad in 
Canada that several western provinces . . . are threatening to secede." Gill 
says that Mexico is in "a state of chaos since NAFTA." Drug trafficking 
is on the rise, crime is burgeoning, farmers are in revolt. "The collapse of 
the peso drove hundreds of small businessmen into bankruptcy," says 
Gill.  "The job losses have been tremendous, in spite of the growth of 
exports to the U.S." Nearly 60 percent of the Mexican workforce is 
unemployed. 
 <p>
As Mexico's internal problems worsen, they pose a growing threat to the 
health and security of the United States. "Even before NAFTA, Mexico 
was the principal conduit for cocaine coming into the U.S. from 
Columbia and other Latin American countries," and the volume has 
increased substantially ever since. "Crime, rampant in Mexico for 
decades, has spilled across the border like a tidal wave in the last two 
years." 
 <p>
William Gill contends that "the American people, like the Mexicans and 
Canadians, have all been made the victims of a gigantic fraud -- the 
biggest scam in history." He argues that there is "only one way to halt the 
insanity  NAFTA and GATT are spreading across America and around 
the world. And that is to roll back both of these fraudulent treaties." Gill 
insists that "NAFTA must be abrogated. America and Mexico cannot 
keep on absorbing the terrible punishment this treaty has inflicted upon 
the people of both countries." 
 <p>
Gill's group, the American Coalition for Competitive Trade, is filing 
several legal challenges to NAFTA and GATT and the $53 billion bailout 
of Mexico. The Coalition wants to block the implementation of these 
treaties before they cause any more damage to our sovereignty and to our 
economy. 
 <p>                           <P><i>Behind The Headlines is produced by America's Future, a nonprofit educational organization dedicated to the preservation of our free enterprise system and our constitutional form of government. For a free transcript of this broadcast, write: America's Future, 7800 Bonhomme, St. Louis, Missouri 63105.</i><p><br><br><center><br><a href="/townhall/tbut.map"><img src="/townhall/tbut.gif" ismap border="0"></a></center></body></html>
