<html><HEAD><TITLE>Duplantier:  Foster Facts -- 1/16/96</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"><a href="/townhall/columnists/"><img align="right" vspace="10" src="/townhall/columnists/thcolm.gif"></a><center>
<h4>BEHIND THE HEADLINES </h4><i>Commentary from America's Future, Inc.<br><a href="/townhall/columnists/duplbio.html">F.R. Duplantier</a> <br>January 16, 1996<br></i><hr><h2>Foster Facts</h2></center>
<P> 

[There 's something shy about the 1993 death of White House Counsel 
Vincent Foster. Could he have known too much about the scandals 
dogging the President?]
<P>
Investigative reporter Christopher Ruddy has identified numerous 
inconsistencies in the official investigations of Vincent Foster's so-called 
suicide. First, there was no suicide note. Then there was a suicide note, 
only it didn't actually mention suicide or bid farewell to family members. 
The 28 torn pieces of the note were found in a briefcase that had been 
searched at least once already, the note had no fingerprints on it, and 
three handwriting experts have declared it a forgery.
<P>
The condition of the body was odd, to say the least. Ruddy says two 
paramedics observed that the slain White House official appeared to be 
"ready for the coffin,'' with arms and legs neatly arranged and head facing 
straight up. There was less blood than might be expected "from a gunshot 
wound to a living person's head." There was no trace of soil on Foster's 
shoes, as there surely would have been had he walked through dense 
brush to the secluded spot where his-body was found. The FBI found 
carpet fibers all over Foster's clothing, but never bothered to determine 
where or why it had come into contact with carpeting.
<P>
The gun was found in Foster's hand, a rarity for suicides. Nevertheless, 
there were no fingerprints on the weapon, says Ruddy. Although Foster 
supposedly shot himself in the mouth, there was "no visible blood 
splatter" on the gun, the recoil did not "chip or damage teeth," and no 
gunpowder was found on his tongue. No one heard the fatal shot, and the 
fired bullet was "never found, despite exhaustive searches."
<P>
Ruddy says Park Police did not "bother to interview park neighbors or 
regular visitors." They failed to "take statements from all persons found 
in the park." They misrepresented the statement of at least one witness. 
They failed to seal Foster's office and "gave away key crime scene 
evidence, such as his beeper and papers, within hours of his death." They 
neglected to have the gun tested "until one week after" the death was 
ruled a suicide. All of the 35-millimeter crime scene photos have 
disappeared, as have seven Polaroids taken at the scene by a Park Police 
officer. The X-rays mentioned in the autopsy report are also missing.
<P>
During the first official investigation of the Foster death, a witness who 
discovered the body was allegedly badgered by- the FBI "to alter his 
testimony on critical issues." Ruddy says another witness charges that the 
FBI lied in claiming he "could not identify a man he saw in the park." 
Investigators simply ignored the statements of other witnesses "who said 
two men, not Foster, were in and around his car just before the body was 
found." The lead prosecutor in the second official probe "resigned after 
being thwarted" in his efforts to conduct a comprehensive investigation. 
Somebody pretty powerful must not want us to know what really 
happened to Vincent Foster.
<P>
(NOTE: <i>For a copy of Vincent Foster: The Ruddy Investigation</i>, call the 
Western Journalism Center at 1-800-711-1968.)
<p>                           <P>
